<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-pop-logistic" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Solving the Logistic Equation</title>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       INTRO PROSE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    In the previous page we set up the logistic equation
    <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = kP(M - P)</m>
    as a model for population growth that accounts for crowding and resource limits.
    Now let's actually solve it. The algebra is a workout, so we have organized things
    so you can read the big picture first and dig into the details later when you need
    them for homework.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       EXAMPLE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <example xml:id="ex-logistic-solve">
    <title>Solving a Logistic Equation</title>
    <p>
      The birth rate of a population <m>P</m> is the constant 20 and the death rate is
      proportional to <m>P</m> with proportionality constant 4. Set up and solve the
      resulting differential equation for <m>P(t)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = \beta P - \alpha P</m> with <m>\beta = 20</m>
      and <m>\alpha = 4P</m>:
      <md>
        <mrow>\frac{dP}{dt} \amp= 20P - (4P)P = 4P(5 - P).</mrow>
      </md>
      This is the logistic equation with <m>k = 4</m> and <m>M = 5</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Step 1: Equilibrium solutions.</alert>
      Setting <m>4P(5 - P) = 0</m> gives
      <me>P(t) = 0 \qquad \text{and} \qquad P(t) = 5.</me>
    </p>

    <solution>
      <title>Work for equilibrium solutions (if stuck)</title>
      <p>
        Constant solutions satisfy <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 0</m>. So we solve
        <me>4P(5 - P) = 0,</me>
        which gives <m>P = 0</m> or <m>5 - P = 0</m>, that is <m>P = 5</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>

    <p>
      <alert>Step 2: Separate variables.</alert>
      For non-equilibrium solutions:
      <me>\frac{1}{P(5 - P)}\, dP = 4\, dt.</me>
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Step 3: Integrate both sides.</alert>
      <me>\int \frac{1}{P(5-P)}\,dP = \int 4\,dt</me>
      gives
      <me>\ln\left|\frac{P}{5-P}\right| = 20t + C, \qquad \text{so} \qquad \frac{P}{5-P} = Ce^{20t}.</me>
    </p>

    <solution>
      <title>Full LHS integration with partial fractions (can skim for now, useful for homework)</title>
      <p>
        We use partial fractions. Write
        <me>\frac{1}{P(5-P)} = \frac{A}{P} + \frac{B}{5-P}.</me>
        Multiplying both sides by <m>P(5-P)</m> and matching coefficients:
        <me>1 = A(5-P) + BP = (-A+B)P + 5A.</me>
        So <m>A = \tfrac{1}{5}</m> and <m>B = \tfrac{1}{5}</m>. Therefore:
        <md>
          <mrow>\int \frac{1}{P(5-P)}\,dP
            \amp= \frac{1}{5}\int \frac{dP}{P} + \frac{1}{5}\int \frac{dP}{5-P}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= \frac{1}{5}\ln|P| - \frac{1}{5}\ln|5-P|.</mrow>
        </md>
        Multiplying through by 5 and using log rules:
        <me>\ln\left|\frac{P}{5-P}\right| = 20t + C.</me>
        Exponentiating: <m>\dfrac{P}{5-P} = Ce^{20t}</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>

  <p>
  <alert>Step 4: Solve for <m>P(t)</m>.</alert>
  The general solution is
  <me>P(t) = \frac{5}{Ce^{-20t} + 1} \quad \text{or} \quad P(t) = 0,</me>
  where <m>C</m> is any real number. Note that <m>C = 0</m> recovers the equilibrium
  solution <m>P(t) = 5</m>. The equilibrium solution <m>P(t) = 0</m> is not captured
  by this formula and must be noted separately.
</p>
    <solution>
      <title>Algebra: solving for <m>P</m> explicitly (can skim for now)</title>
      <p>
        Starting from <m>\dfrac{P}{5-P} = Ce^{20t}</m>, take reciprocals of both sides:
        <me>\frac{5-P}{P} = \frac{1}{C}e^{-20t}.</me>
        Split the left side:
        <me>\frac{5}{P} - 1 = \frac{1}{C}e^{-20t}.</me>
        Relabeling <m>\tfrac{1}{C}</m> as <m>C</m>:
        <me>\frac{5}{P} = Ce^{-20t} + 1.</me>
        Taking reciprocals:
        <me>P(t) = \frac{5}{Ce^{-20t} + 1}.</me>
      </p>
    </solution>

  </example>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       TRANSITION PROSE TO MC
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    Now that we have an explicit formula for <m>P(t)</m>, one of the most important
    questions in population modelling is: what happens in the long run?
    Does the population grow forever, crash to zero, or stabilize at some value?
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       MC CHECKPOINT
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <exercise xml:id="ex-mc-logistic-limit">
    <statement>
      <p>
        In the solution <m>P(t) = \dfrac{5}{Ce^{-20t} + 1}</m>,
        what is <m>\displaystyle\lim_{t \to \infty} P(t)</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice>
        <statement><p><m>0</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not quite. Think about what happens to <m>e^{-20t}</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
            It decays to zero, not grows. So the denominator does not blow up.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p><m>5</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Correct! As <m>t \to \infty</m>, <m>e^{-20t} \to 0</m>, so
            <m>Ce^{-20t} + 1 \to 1</m>, giving <m>P(t) \to \dfrac{5}{1} = 5</m>.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p><m>\infty</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not quite. Since <m>e^{-20t} \to 0</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
            the denominator approaches 1, not 0. So <m>P(t)</m> does not blow up.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>It depends on <m>C</m>.</p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Good instinct, but notice that <m>Ce^{-20t} \to 0</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>
            regardless of what <m>C</m> is. The limit is the same for every solution.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       CARRYING CAPACITY PROSE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    That limit equals exactly <m>M = 5</m>, the carrying capacity. This is not a coincidence.
    For the logistic equation with <m>k \gt 0</m>, every solution with <m>P(0) \gt 0</m> satisfies
    <me>\lim_{t \to \infty} P(t) = M.</me>
    No matter where the population starts, it always levels off at the carrying capacity. 
    Also notice that <m>P(0) = 0</m> we recover one of the equilibrium solutions: if the population starts at zero, it stays there.
    A similar thing happens for <m>P(0) = 5</m>!
    This is exactly the realistic, well-behaved growth we were hoping to model.
  </p>
<figure xml:id="fig-logistic-curves">
  <caption>
    Solution curves for <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 4P(5-P)</m>. For any <m>P(0) \gt 0</m>,
    the population converges to the carrying capacity <m>M = 5</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
    If <m>P(0) = 0</m>, then <m>P(t) = 0</m> for all <m>t</m>.
    Use the slider to set the initial value and press Play to watch the solution evolve.
  </caption>
  <interactive xml:id="interactive-logistic-curves"
    iframe="ch2-graph/interactive-logistic-curves.html" width="100%" aspect="3:2">
    <static>
      <p>
        Animated solution curve for <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 4P(5-P)</m> with a slider for
        <m>P(0)</m> from 0 to 8. For any positive initial value, the curve converges to
        the carrying capacity <m>M = 5</m>. If <m>P(0) = 0</m>, the population stays
        at zero for all time. Dashed lines mark the equilibrium solutions <m>P = 0</m>
        and <m>P = 5</m>.
      </p>
    </static>
  </interactive>
</figure>
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       GRAPH PLACEHOLDER
  JSXGraph interactive showing several solution curves for dP/dt = 4P(5-P)
  with different initial conditions, all converging to M = 5.
  Dashed horizontal line at P = 5 labelled "M = 5 (carrying capacity)".
  Place here so students see the S-curve right after understanding the limit.
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <!-- GRAPH PLACEHOLDER: interactive-logistic-curves.html -->

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       CONCLUSION: TEASER FOR NEXT SECTION
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    The logistic equation with <m>k \gt 0</m> is a beautifully behaved model. Solutions
    are bounded, they stabilize, and the long-term behavior is completely predictable
    regardless of initial conditions. In the next section we look at a similar model
    with <m>k \lt 0</m>, and we find much more pathological behavior: populations that
    go extinct in finite time and populations that explode to infinity in finite time.
  </p>

